          "body": "The first oracle opens by restating Balak's commission in full (23:7) before immediately collapsing it with a rhetorical question: 'How shall I curse whom God has not cursed? And how can I denounce whom the LORD has not denounced?' (23:8). The grammar of impossibility is decisive. Balaam then describes Israel from his elevated vantage point (23:9): a people set apart, not to be reckoned among the nations. The word badad ('apart') is the same root used of the leper required to dwell outside the camp (Leviticus 13:46) — here the connotation is inverted from exclusion to consecration. Israel's separateness is not social marginalization but divine designation. The oracle closes with an extraordinary personal longing (23:10): 'Let me die the death of the upright, and let my end be like his!' — the foremost enemy prophet, commissioned to curse, instead envies the final destiny of those he was supposed to destroy. Tim Keller observed that genuine encounter with the blessing of God produces not envy but longing to share in it; Balaam's closing wish is his most honest moment in the entire Pentateuch."
