          "body": "Balak's repeated reactions structure the chapter's argument as much as the oracles themselves. After the first oracle, Balak protests: 'What have you done to me? I took you to curse my enemies, but behold, you have actually blessed them!' (23:11). His solution is geographic: a new vantage point where only part of Israel is visible (23:13). After the second oracle, his frustration reaches a ceiling: 'Do not curse them at all nor bless them at all!' (23:25) — a demand that the entire prophetic operation stop. Neither the repositioning nor the shutdown command alters anything. Balak's escalating desperation is the narrator's proof that the covenant-protection is not fragile, not dependent on Israel's awareness of the threat, and not vulnerable to the most politically powerful and religiously sophisticated opposition Moab can muster. Israel is camped obliviously (23:21 — the LORD their God is with them, the shout of a king is among them) while their protection is being argued out in the high places above them. God guards what He has blessed."
