        "excerpt": "Build seven altars for me here, and prepare seven bulls and seven rams for me here.",
        "body": "The chapter opens with Balaam directing a sacrificial installation that is, by any ancient Near Eastern standard, maximal. Seven altars, seven bulls, seven rams — the number seven being the Hebrew number of completeness and wholeness. This is not merely expensive; it is theologically extravagant, the ancient equivalent of every available spiritual resource deployed at once. Balak complies immediately and completely (23:2). The narrator pauses to note that both king and prophet participated in the offerings — this is not a proxy ceremony; Balak himself is present at the altar, invested at the highest level.\n\nBut the ritual setup immediately reveals its own contradiction. Balaam says to Balak: 'Stand beside your burnt offering, and I will go; perhaps the LORD will come to meet me' (23:3). The word 'perhaps' (Hebrew ulay) is the crack in the entire enterprise. Balaam, despite his professional credentials and international reputation, cannot guarantee a divine encounter. He can only position himself and hope. This is the ancient dilemma of all pagan religious manipulation: you can assemble the rituals, but you cannot command the god. The LORD meets Balaam not because of the seven altars but according to His own sovereign initiative (23:4, 16).\n\nThe narrative detail that Balaam 'went to a bare hill' (23:3, Hebrew shephi — a barren height, stripped of vegetation) is suggestive. Stripped of the ceremonial apparatus, alone, Balaam encounters the God of Israel. The altars did not produce the encounter; solitude before the living God did. The theology of encounter here is anti-ritualistic: what matters is not the expenditure of sacrifice but the will of the One being sought.\n\nGod's response when He meets Balaam is utterly simple and totally controlling: 'Return to Balak, and you shall speak thus' (23:5). The divine speech is not a dialogue; it is an instruction. Yahweh does not negotiate the content of the oracle with Balaam; He places a word in his mouth (23:5) and sends him back. The Hebrew sum ('put' or 'place') is the same verb used of God placing the sun and moon in the sky (Genesis 1:17). The word Balaam will speak is as fixed as the celestial bodies — placed, not suggested.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Ulay* (perhaps, 23:3) — the particle of uncertainty or hope; used also in Genesis 18:24 (Abraham's intercession) and 1 Samuel 14:6 (Jonathan's faith). Its appearance in Balaam's mouth reveals the limits of his confidence despite his reputation. *Sum* (put/place, 23:5) — to set firmly, to appoint; the same verb as 'set a boundary' and 'establish a throne' elsewhere in the Pentateuch. The word in Balaam's mouth is set, not merely suggested."
